JavaScript modules are a mechanism for splitting programs into separate modules that can be imported when needed. Modules provide encapsulation, clean global scope, and better code organization.

A module is just a file. One script is one module. Modules use export and import directives to exchange functionality.

The export keyword marks variables and functions for external access. The import directive loads the module and assigns exported features to variables.

Before native modules, various systems were used:

CommonJS — for Node.js, uses require/exports, synchronous loading
AMD — asynchronous module loading, used in RequireJS
UMD — universal system, compatible with AMD and CommonJS
ES6 Modules — official built-in system, supported by all browsers and Node.js

Exporting module features with export:

export const name = "square";
export function draw() { ... }
export class Shape { ... }

Or with a single statement at the end:

export { name, draw, reportArea };

With aliases:

export { name as userName, draw as drawShape };

Importing features with import:

import { name, draw } from './modules/square.js';

With alias:

import { name as userName } from './modules/square.js';

Import everything as an object:

import * as Square from './modules/square.js';
Square.draw();

Dynamic imports with import() return a promise and allow loading code on demand:

import('./modules/square.js')
  .then(module => {
    module.draw();
  });

Key Features:

Strict mode — modules always use strict mode
Module-level scope — each module has its own scope
Single evaluation — code executes only on first import

import.meta — contains information about the current module - console.log(import.meta.url);

Browser-Specific Features:

Deferred execution — modules wait for document loading
HTTP(s) requirement — local server needed for testing
type="module" — indicates that the script is a module:

<script type="module" src="main.js"></script>

Best Practices:

1. Use import/export instead of global variables
2. Export functions for multiple calls
3. Use relative paths for better portability
4. Avoid circular dependencies
5. Use dynamic imports for optimizing loading

Queue is a data structure that operates on the FIFO principle (First In, First Out).

Basic Operations:

enqueue — add an element to the end of the queue
dequeue — remove an element from the front of the queue
front — view the first element without removing

How It Works:

Elements are added at one end (tail) and removed from the other end (head). The first element added will be the first one removed.

Example in JavaScript:

const queue = [];
queue.push(1); // [1]
queue.push(2); // [1, 2]
queue.push(3); // [1, 2, 3]
queue.shift(); // 1, queue becomes [2, 3]

Optimized Implementation:

class Queue {
  constructor() {
    this.items = [];
    this.front = 0;
  }
  enqueue(element) {
    this.items.push(element);
  }
  dequeue() {
    return this.items[this.front++];
  }
}

Applications in Programming:

Task management and schedulers. Server request handling. Breadth-first search (BFS) traversal. Data buffering. Message queue systems.

Characteristics:

Time complexity O(1) for enqueue and dequeue (with optimized implementation). Implemented with arrays or linked lists. Maintains processing order.

Deque (Double-Ended Queue) is a data structure that allows adding and removing elements from both ends.

Basic Deque Operations:

pushFront — add element to the front
pushBack — add element to the back
popFront — remove element from the front
popBack — remove element from the back
peekFront — view the first element
peekBack — view the last element

Deque Example:

const deque = [];
deque.unshift(1); // [1] - pushFront
deque.push(2);    // [1, 2] - pushBack
deque.shift();    // 1 - popFront
deque.pop();      // 2 - popBack

Deque Applications:

Task schedulers. Sliding window average. History handling (undo/redo). Tree traversal. Data buffering.

Priority Queue:

A data structure where each element has a priority. Elements are removed based on priority (highest priority first), not insertion order.

Basic Operations:

enqueue — add element with priority
dequeue — remove element with highest priority
peek — view element with highest priority

Heap-Based Implementation:

class PriorityQueue {
  constructor() {
    this.heap = [];
  }
  enqueue(value, priority) {
    this.heap.push({ value, priority });
    this.bubbleUp();
  }
  dequeue() {
    const max = this.heap[0];
    const last = this.heap.pop();
    if (this.heap.length) {
      this.heap[0] = last;
      this.sinkDown();
    }
    return max;
  }
}

Priority Queue Applications:

Dijkstra's algorithm (shortest path). OS task scheduling. Urgent request handling. Compression algorithms (Huffman coding). Event management systems.

Characteristics:

Deque: O(1) for operations on both ends. Priority Queue: O(log n) for insert and remove (with heap), O(n) for array-based implementation.

Error handling in JavaScript is a mechanism for catching and managing exceptional situations that occur during program execution.

try...catch...finally:

try — block where an error may occur
catch — block executed when an error occurs
finally — block always executed (regardless of error)

Syntax:

try {
  // code that may throw an error
} catch (error) {
  // error handling
  console.error(error.message);
} finally {
  // code that always executes
}

Error Object:

name — error type (Error, TypeError, SyntaxError, etc.)
message — error description
stack — call stack (where error occurred)

Error Types:

Error — base type
SyntaxError — syntax error
ReferenceError — accessing undeclared variable
TypeError — invalid value type
RangeError — value out of allowed range
URIError — error in URI functions
EvalError — error in eval()

Creating Custom Errors:

throw new Error('Custom error');
throw new TypeError('Invalid type');

class ValidationError extends Error {
  constructor(message) {
    super(message);
    this.name = 'ValidationError';
  }
}

throw new ValidationError('Invalid data');

Asynchronous Errors:

Promises: .catch()
async/await: try...catch

// Promises
fetch('/api')
  .then(response => response.json())
  .catch(error => console.error(error));

// async/await
try {
  const response = await fetch('/api');
  const data = await response.json();
} catch (error) {
  console.error(error);
}

Best Practices:

Do not suppress errors (empty catch). Always handle asynchronous errors. Create custom error types. Use finally for resource cleanup. Log errors for debugging. Do not use throw for flow control (anti-pattern).

Special Cases:

Errors in setTimeout are not caught by outer try...catch. Promise errors require .catch() or try...catch with await. Uncaught errors can be caught via window.onerror (browser) or process.on('uncaughtException') (Node.js).
